'''Mu'adh ibn Muslim ibn Mu'adh''' was a general and governor for the [[Abbasid Caliphate]].
He was a Persian from [[Khuttal]] or [[Rey, Iran|Rayy]], who converted and became a ''[[mawla]]'' of the [[Banu Dhuhl]] tribe. He participated in the [[Abbasid Revolution]] in 737/738, and was a partisan of [[Abu Muslim]]. In 766, he was among the army of [[Marw al-Rudh]] which was defeated by the rebel [[al-Muqanna]]. He served as governor of [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] in 778–780, and fought against the [[Alids]] in 785/786. He probably died shortly after.
He was closely connected to the Abbasid family, and his family continued to enjoy high office: one of his sons, Husayn, was a foster-brother of Caliph [[al-Hadi]], while another son, [[Yahya ibn Mu'adh ibn Muslim|Yahya]], served as governor of [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]] and [[Arminiya|Armenia]].
